[3] Thailand, OIE report
Date: Wed 7 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE Update On Avian Influenza In Animals In Asia (Type H5) [edited]
<http://oie.int/downld/AVIAN%20INFLUENZA/Thailand%20Follow-up%20Report%20No19.pdf>

Thailand follow-up report No. 19
--------------------------------------
Information received on 7 Jul 2004 from Dr. Yukol Limlamthong,
Director General, Department of Livestock Development, Ministry of
Agriculture and Cooperatives, Bangkok:
Previous follow-up report: No 18 of 5 Jul 2004.
Disease name: Highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI)
Nature of diagnosis: Clinical, Post-mortem, Laboratory.
Date of initial detection of lesions/clinical signs: 6 Jul 2004
Estimated date of primary infection: 4 Jul 2004
Location: Bang-Kra-dee subdistrict, Muang district, Pathumthani province
Species/susceptible/deaths/destroyed/slaughtered
avians/850/120/730/-
Description of affected population: Layers
Laboratory where diagnosis was made: National Institute of Animal Health
Diagnostic tests used: Virus isolation by egg inoculation,
Hemagglutination, Hemagglutination Inhibition Assay
Causal agent: Highly pathogenic avian influenza virus type A (H5)
Source of agent/origin of infection: Under investigation
Mode of spread: Under investigation
Control measures during reporting period: Stamping out; vaccination
prohibited; quarantine; movement control inside country; screening;
zoning.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
