[4] China, OIE report
Date: Wed 7 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE Disease Alert [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/Messages/040707PRC.htm>

Highly pathogenic avian influenza (virus type H5N1) in the People's
Republic of China
-----------------------------------------------
(Date of previous outbreak of highly pathogenic avian influenza in
the People's Republic of China reported to the OIE: February 2004).
Information received on 6 Jul 2004 from Dr. Shen Zhenzhao, Director
General, Bureau of Animal Husbandry and Health, Ministry of
Agriculture, Beijing.
Date of the report: 6 Jul 2004.
An outbreak of highly pathogenic avian influenza was reported in
Juchao district, Chaohu city, Anhui province.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 28 Jun 2004.
Date of virus isolation: 5 Jul 2004.
Estimated date of primary infection: 24 Jun 2004.
Number of susceptible animals in the outbreak: 8160.
Number of cases: 1850.
Number of deaths: 1520.
Number of animals destroyed: 6640.
Source of agent/origin of infection: the farm is close to Chaohu
lake; it is very possible that the disease was transmitted by
migratory birds and wild waterfowl.
Control measures:
- stamping out;
- quarantine and movement control inside the country;
- vaccination.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Clearly, the current problems associated with avian influenza in
Eastern Asia are not over yet. Viet Nam, Cambodia, and, now, China
are reporting fresh outbreaks. There are also reports of an upswing
of cases in Thailand and Indonesia.
When an epidemic becomes a low-level smoldering fire in animal
populations, you can rest assured that new flocks or herds will serve
as fresh fuel, and the epidemic will surge. That is why it is so
important to stamp out the disease and to maintain very vigorous
surveillance for ample periods of time after apparent freedom from
disease.
Let's hope that this will be a typical mopping-up operation aimed at
a few stray bird farms. However, the occurrence of new outbreaks from
so many different countries, within the span of a few days, may
indicate another round in the struggle to truly rid East Asian
poultry of this highly pathogenic influenza virus. - Mod.PC]
[Data on the vaccine applied as a post-infection control measure in
China (homologous?) and the full identity of the virus described as
H5 in Thailand will be helpful. - Mod. AS].
